#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.8.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "This release supports  Python 2.6 -2.7 and 3.2 - 3.3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:9
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:12
msgid ""
"New, no 2to3, Python 2 and Python 3 are supported by a common code base."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:13
msgid "New, gufuncs for linear algebra, enabling operations on stacked arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:14
msgid "New, inplace fancy indexing for ufuncs with the ``.at`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:15
msgid ""
"New, ``partition`` function, partial sorting via selection for fast median."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:16
msgid "New, ``nanmean``, ``nanvar``, and ``nanstd`` functions skipping NaNs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:17
msgid ""
"New, ``full`` and ``full_like`` functions to create value initialized arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:18
msgid ""
"New, ``PyUFunc_RegisterLoopForDescr``, better ufunc support for user dtypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:19
msgid "Numerous performance improvements in many areas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:23
msgid "Dropped Support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:26
msgid "Support for Python versions 2.4 and 2.5 has been dropped,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:28
msgid "Support for SCons has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:32
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:35
msgid ""
"The Datetime64 type remains experimental in this release. In 1.9 there will "
"probably be some changes to make it more usable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:38
msgid ""
"The diagonal method currently returns a new array and raises a "
"FutureWarning. In 1.9 it will return a readonly view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:41
msgid ""
"Multiple field selection from an array of structured type currently returns "
"a new array and raises a FutureWarning. In 1.9 it will return a readonly "
"view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:45
msgid ""
"The numpy/oldnumeric and numpy/numarray compatibility modules will be "
"removed in 1.9."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:50
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:53
msgid ""
"The doc/sphinxext content has been moved into its own github repository, and "
"is included in numpy as a submodule. See the instructions in doc/"
"HOWTO_BUILD_DOCS.rst for how to access the content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:59
msgid ""
"The hash function of numpy.void scalars has been changed.  Previously the "
"pointer to the data was hashed as an integer.  Now, the hash function uses "
"the tuple-hash algorithm to combine the hash functions of the elements of "
"the scalar, but only if the scalar is read-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:64
msgid ""
"Numpy has switched its build system to using 'separate compilation' by "
"default.  In previous releases this was supported, but not default. This "
"should produce the same results as the old system, but if you're trying to "
"do something complicated like link numpy statically or using an unusual "
"compiler, then it's possible you will encounter problems. If so, please file "
"a bug and as a temporary workaround you can re-enable the old build system "
"by exporting the shell variable NPY_SEPARATE_COMPILATION=0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"For the AdvancedNew iterator the ``oa_ndim`` flag should now be -1 to "
"indicate that no ``op_axes`` and ``itershape`` are passed in. The ``oa_ndim "
"== 0`` case, now indicates a 0-D iteration and ``op_axes`` being NULL and "
"the old usage is deprecated. This does not effect the ``NpyIter_New`` or "
"``NpyIter_MultiNew`` functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:78
msgid ""
"The functions nanargmin and nanargmax now return np.iinfo['intp'].min for "
"the index in all-NaN slices. Previously the functions would raise a "
"ValueError for array returns and NaN for scalar returns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:83
msgid "NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:84
msgid ""
"There is a new compile time environment variable "
"``NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING``. If this variable is set to 1, then numpy "
"will consider more arrays to be C- or F-contiguous -- for example, it "
"becomes possible to have a column vector which is considered both C- and F-"
"contiguous simultaneously. The new definition is more accurate, allows for "
"faster code that makes fewer unnecessary copies, and simplifies numpy's code "
"internally. However, it may also break third-party libraries that make too-"
"strong assumptions about the stride values of C- and F-contiguous arrays. "
"(It is also currently known that this breaks Cython code using memoryviews, "
"which will be fixed in Cython.) THIS WILL BECOME THE DEFAULT IN A FUTURE "
"RELEASE, SO PLEASE TEST YOUR CODE NOW AGAINST NUMPY BUILT WITH::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:97
msgid "NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING=1 python setup.py install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:99
msgid ""
"You can check whether NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING is in effect by running::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:102
msgid "np.ones((10, 1), order=\"C\").flags.f_contiguous"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:104
msgid ""
"This will be ``True`` if relaxed strides checking is enabled, and ``False`` "
"otherwise. The typical problem we've seen so far is C code that works with C-"
"contiguous arrays, and assumes that the itemsize can be accessed by looking "
"at the last element in the ``PyArray_STRIDES(arr)`` array. When relaxed "
"strides are in effect, this is not true (and in fact, it never was true in "
"some corner cases). Instead, use ``PyArray_ITEMSIZE(arr)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:112
msgid ""
"For more information check the \"Internal memory layout of an ndarray\" "
"section in the documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:116
msgid "Binary operations with non-arrays as second argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:117
msgid ""
"Binary operations of the form ``<array-or-subclass> * <non-array-subclass>`` "
"where ``<non-array-subclass>`` declares an ``__array_priority__`` higher "
"than that of ``<array-or-subclass>`` will now unconditionally return "
"*NotImplemented*, giving ``<non-array-subclass>`` a chance to handle the "
"operation.  Previously, `NotImplemented` would only be returned if ``<non-"
"array-subclass>`` actually implemented the reversed operation, and after a "
"(potentially expensive) array conversion of ``<non-array-subclass>`` had "
"been attempted. (`bug <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/3375>`_, `pull "
"request <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/3501>`_)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:128
msgid ""
"Function `median` used with `overwrite_input` only partially sorts array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:129
msgid ""
"If `median` is used with `overwrite_input` option the input array will now "
"only be partially sorted instead of fully sorted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:133
msgid "Fix to financial.npv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:134
msgid ""
"The npv function had a bug. Contrary to what the documentation stated, it "
"summed from indexes ``1`` to ``M`` instead of from ``0`` to ``M - 1``. The "
"fix changes the returned value. The mirr function called the npv function, "
"but worked around the problem, so that was also fixed and the return value "
"of the mirr function remains unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:141
msgid "Runtime warnings when comparing NaN numbers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:142
msgid ""
"Comparing ``NaN`` floating point numbers now raises the ``invalid`` runtime "
"warning. If a ``NaN`` is expected the warning can be ignored using np."
"errstate. E.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:146
msgid ""
"with np.errstate(invalid='ignore'):\n"
"    operation()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:151
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:155
msgid "Support for linear algebra on stacked arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:156
msgid ""
"The gufunc machinery is now used for np.linalg, allowing operations on "
"stacked arrays and vectors. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:159
msgid ""
">>> a\n"
"array([[[ 1.,  1.],\n"
"        [ 0.,  1.]],\n"
"\n"
"       [[ 1.,  1.],\n"
"        [ 0.,  1.]]])\n"
"\n"
">>> np.linalg.inv(a)\n"
"array([[[ 1., -1.],\n"
"        [ 0.,  1.]],\n"
"\n"
"       [[ 1., -1.],\n"
"        [ 0.,  1.]]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:174
msgid "In place fancy indexing for ufuncs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:175
msgid ""
"The function ``at`` has been added to ufunc objects to allow in place ufuncs "
"with no buffering when fancy indexing is used. For example, the following "
"will increment the first and second items in the array, and will increment "
"the third item twice: ``numpy.add.at(arr, [0, 1, 2, 2], 1)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:180
msgid ""
"This is what many have mistakenly thought ``arr[[0, 1, 2, 2]] += 1`` would "
"do, but that does not work as the incremented value of ``arr[2]`` is simply "
"copied into the third slot in ``arr`` twice, not incremented twice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:185
msgid "New functions `partition` and `argpartition`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "New functions to partially sort arrays via a selection algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:188
msgid ""
"A ``partition`` by index ``k`` moves the ``k`` smallest element to the front "
"of an array.  All elements before ``k`` are then smaller or equal than the "
"value in position ``k`` and all elements following ``k`` are then greater or "
"equal than the value in position ``k``. The ordering of the values within "
"these bounds is undefined. A sequence of indices can be provided to sort all "
"of them into their sorted position at once iterative partitioning. This can "
"be used to efficiently obtain order statistics like median or percentiles of "
"samples. ``partition`` has a linear time complexity of ``O(n)`` while a full "
"sort has ``O(n log(n))``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:201
msgid "New functions `nanmean`, `nanvar` and `nanstd`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:202
msgid ""
"New nan aware statistical functions are added. In these functions the "
"results are what would be obtained if nan values were omitted from all "
"computations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "New functions `full` and `full_like`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:208
msgid ""
"New convenience functions to create arrays filled with a specific value; "
"complementary to the existing `zeros` and `zeros_like` functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:212
msgid "IO compatibility with large files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:213
msgid "Large NPZ files >2GB can be loaded on 64-bit systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:216
msgid "Building against OpenBLAS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:217
msgid "It is now possible to build numpy against OpenBLAS by editing site.cfg."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:220
msgid "New constant"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:221
msgid "Euler's constant is now exposed in numpy as euler_gamma."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:224
msgid "New modes for qr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:225
msgid ""
"New modes 'complete', 'reduced', and 'raw' have been added to the qr "
"factorization and the old 'full' and 'economic' modes are deprecated. The "
"'reduced' mode replaces the old 'full' mode and is the default as was the "
"'full' mode, so backward compatibility can be maintained by not specifying "
"the mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:231
msgid ""
"The 'complete' mode returns a full dimensional factorization, which can be "
"useful for obtaining a basis for the orthogonal complement of the range "
"space. The 'raw' mode returns arrays that contain the Householder reflectors "
"and scaling factors that can be used in the future to apply q without "
"needing to convert to a matrix. The 'economic' mode is simply deprecated, "
"there isn't much use for it and it isn't any more efficient than the 'raw' "
"mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:240
msgid "New `invert` argument to `in1d`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:241
msgid ""
"The function `in1d` now accepts a `invert` argument which, when `True`, "
"causes the returned array to be inverted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:245
msgid "Advanced indexing using `np.newaxis`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:246
msgid ""
"It is now possible to use `np.newaxis`/`None` together with index arrays "
"instead of only in simple indices. This means that ``array[np.newaxis, [0, "
"1]]`` will now work as expected and select the first two rows while "
"prepending a new axis to the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:253
msgid "C-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:254
msgid ""
"New ufuncs can now be registered with builtin input types and a custom "
"output type. Before this change, NumPy wouldn't be able to find the right "
"ufunc loop function when the ufunc was called from Python, because the ufunc "
"loop signature matching logic wasn't looking at the output operand type. Now "
"the correct ufunc loop is found, as long as the user provides an output "
"argument with the correct output type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:262
msgid "runtests.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:263
msgid ""
"A simple test runner script ``runtests.py`` was added. It also builds Numpy "
"via ``setup.py build`` and can be used to run tests easily during "
"development."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:268
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:271
msgid "IO performance improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:272
msgid ""
"Performance in reading large files was improved by chunking (see also IO "
"compatibility)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:275
msgid "Performance improvements to `pad`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:276
msgid ""
"The `pad` function has a new implementation, greatly improving performance "
"for all inputs except `mode=<function>` (retained for backwards "
"compatibility). Scaling with dimensionality is dramatically improved for "
"rank >= 4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:281
msgid "Performance improvements to `isnan`, `isinf`, `isfinite` and `byteswap`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:282
msgid ""
"`isnan`, `isinf`, `isfinite` and `byteswap` have been improved to take "
"advantage of compiler builtins to avoid expensive calls to libc. This "
"improves performance of these operations by about a factor of two on gnu "
"libc systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:288
msgid "Performance improvements via SSE2 vectorization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:289
msgid ""
"Several functions have been optimized to make use of SSE2 CPU SIMD "
"instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:294
msgid "Float32 and float64:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:292
msgid "base math (`add`, `subtract`, `divide`, `multiply`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:293
msgid "`sqrt`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:294
msgid "`minimum/maximum`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:295
msgid "`absolute`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:299
msgid "Bool:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:297
msgid "`logical_or`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:298
msgid "`logical_and`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:299
msgid "`logical_not`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:301
msgid ""
"This improves performance of these operations up to 4x/2x for float32/"
"float64 and up to 10x for bool depending on the location of the data in the "
"CPU caches. The performance gain is greatest for in-place operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:305
msgid ""
"In order to use the improved functions the SSE2 instruction set must be "
"enabled at compile time. It is enabled by default on x86_64 systems. On "
"x86_32 with a capable CPU it must be enabled by passing the appropriate flag "
"to the CFLAGS build variable (-msse2 with gcc)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:311
msgid "Performance improvements to `median`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:312
msgid ""
"`median` is now implemented in terms of `partition` instead of `sort` which "
"reduces its time complexity from O(n log(n)) to O(n). If used with the "
"`overwrite_input` option the array will now only be partially sorted instead "
"of fully sorted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:319
msgid "Overridable operand flags in ufunc C-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:320
msgid ""
"When creating a ufunc, the default ufunc operand flags can be overridden via "
"the new op_flags attribute of the ufunc object. For example, to set the "
"operand flag for the first input to read/write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:324
msgid ""
"PyObject \\*ufunc = PyUFunc_FromFuncAndData(...); ufunc->op_flags[0] = "
"NPY_ITER_READWRITE;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:327
msgid ""
"This allows a ufunc to perform an operation in place. Also, global nditer "
"flags can be overridden via the new iter_flags attribute of the ufunc "
"object. For example, to set the reduce flag for a ufunc:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:331
msgid "ufunc->iter_flags = NPY_ITER_REDUCE_OK;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:335
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:339 ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:391
msgid "General"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:340
msgid "The function np.take now allows 0-d arrays as indices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:342
msgid "The separate compilation mode is now enabled by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:344
msgid "Several changes to np.insert and np.delete:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:346
msgid ""
"Previously, negative indices and indices that pointed past the end of the "
"array were simply ignored. Now, this will raise a Future or Deprecation "
"Warning. In the future they will be treated like normal indexing treats them "
"-- negative indices will wrap around, and out-of-bound indices will generate "
"an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:351
msgid ""
"Previously, boolean indices were treated as if they were integers (always "
"referring to either the 0th or 1st item in the array). In the future, they "
"will be treated as masks. In this release, they raise a FutureWarning "
"warning of this coming change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:355
msgid ""
"In Numpy 1.7. np.insert already allowed the syntax `np.insert(arr, 3, "
"[1,2,3])` to insert multiple items at a single position. In Numpy 1.8. this "
"is also possible for `np.insert(arr, [3], [1, 2, 3])`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:359
msgid "Padded regions from np.pad are now correctly rounded, not truncated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:362
msgid "C-API Array Additions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:363
msgid "Four new functions have been added to the array C-API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:365
msgid "PyArray_Partition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:366
msgid "PyArray_ArgPartition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:367
msgid "PyArray_SelectkindConverter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:368
msgid "PyDataMem_NEW_ZEROED"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:371
msgid "C-API Ufunc Additions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:372
msgid ""
"One new function has been added to the ufunc C-API that allows to register "
"an inner loop for user types using the descr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:375
msgid "PyUFunc_RegisterLoopForDescr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:378
msgid "C-API Developer Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:379
msgid ""
"The ``PyArray_Type`` instance creation function ``tp_new`` now uses "
"``tp_basicsize`` to determine how much memory to allocate. In previous "
"releases only ``sizeof(PyArrayObject)`` bytes of memory were allocated, "
"often requiring C-API subtypes to reimplement ``tp_new``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:386
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:388
msgid "The 'full' and 'economic' modes of qr factorization are deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.8.0-notes.rst:392
msgid ""
"The use of non-integer for indices and most integer arguments has been "
"deprecated. Previously float indices and function arguments such as axes or "
"shapes were truncated to integers without warning. For example `arr."
"reshape(3., -1)` or `arr[0.]` will trigger a deprecation warning in NumPy "
"1.8., and in some future version of NumPy they will raise an error."
msgstr ""

